text: Fowler's snouted tree frog (Scinax quinquefasciatus) is a frog that lives in Colombia, Ecuador, and Peru. Human beings accidentally brought it to the Galapagos Islands. Scientists have seen it as high as 620 meters above sea level. The adult male frog is 27.6–38.2 mm long from nose to rear end and the adult female frog is 33.9–38.9 mm long. This frog can be in different colors. It can be light brown or dark brown with darker marks and other patterns. Its belly is the color of cream. This frog sometimes has a mark on its stomach that looks like five lines coming out from the same middle. Its Latin name means "five rays." ==References== Category:Frogs of South America
title: Scinax quinquefasciatus
